The outline¶

Data Preparation & Explanatory Analysis¶

  • Taking a look in the data

  • Preparing Variables (Time data & Item size)

  • Adjusting the Data types

  • Explanatory Analysis

  • Data Partioning

  • Outlier and Missing handling

  • Scalization & Normalization

  • Feature Selection (Filter methods)

  • Weight-of-Evidence coding the known & the unknown data sets

  • Forward Regression & Backward Selection methods

    ### Model Building

  • Logistic Regression

  • Decision Trees

  • Regularization

  • Greedy Search Method & Cross Validation

  • Random Forest

  • Extreme Boosting Algorithm

    ### Cost Sensitive Analysis

    ### Getting the unknown data predictions

Note: Why Clustering won't be done?

  • In the known data we have already two clusters as 0 and 1s. In the unknown data, we don't have that but since the aim is to decide whether a customer is going to return a product or not (1 and 0), trying to group individuals according to similarities with respect to each other is something that is not needed. A kind of multi-dimensional scaling map could be done as an explanatory analysis but because of the data set's size being big, it is also not practical to do.

In [7]:
dfu_order_item_id = dfu['order_item_id'] #will be used when the dfu predictions are being indexed at the end.


dfk.drop(['order_item_id', 'user_id'], axis=1, inplace=True)
dfu.drop(['order_item_id', 'user_id'], axis=1, inplace=True)

The ID numbers are dropped above because of the following reasons:¶

  • Some users can be more prone to return the items than the others but keeping the user id column would only help to detect the likelihood of the same user returning an item and since this wouldn't help predicting the behavior of new users, this variable is excluded. Also dummy or WoE encoding over 10,000 users probably won't give us good results.

  • Since Order id functions as just a counter it doesn't convey any meaningful information.

Time Data Fixation¶

  • In order for us to be able to use the variables that are related to time later in the prediction algorithms, they need to be converted to a number.
  • The reason why they are being converted before the actual data exploratory phase is to be able to analyze them too.

In [9]:
now = pd.Timestamp('now')
dfk['user_dob'] = dfk['user_dob'].where(dfk['user_dob'] < now, dfk['user_dob'] -  np.timedelta64(100, 'Y'))   
dfk['user_age'] = (now - dfk['user_dob']).astype('<m8[Y]')    

dfu['user_dob'] = dfu['user_dob'].where(dfu['user_dob'] < now, dfu['user_dob'] -  np.timedelta64(100, 'Y'))   
dfu['user_age'] = (now - dfu['user_dob']).astype('<m8[Y]')

dfu.user_age        #as the difference in months and days wouldn't really be helpful in explaining the return behavior and since
                    #if an item is returned and age plays a role in it, it would be more likely because of the generational
                    # differences such as 5, 10, 20 years but not small differences like 0.1 or 0.2 and etc. Because of that 
                    #user age is tought to be fine when it is calculated in years and not months or days.

In [15]:
dfk=dfk[dfk.delivery_date != ('1994-12-31')]    #omitted 1072 rows.

  • These values are obvious to be a system error. If the delivery date could not been tracked by the online retailer, the system might be filling those values automatically to a date such as the installation date of the tracking system or the like.

  • We do not know yet whether delivery date variable will turnout to be predictive and worth keeping. Rather than omitting them one could calculate the average delivery duration and then impute these values with "order date + average delivery duration" however this might affect the decision whether to keep the variable or not also since the data set we have is big enough, we simply delete these rows.

In [23]:
print(dfk.delivery_date.isnull().sum().sum())

9318

A finding: Every NA value in the delivery date column has a return of 0, which makes it plausable to guess that the customers have not received the item they ordered yet for some reason. If the gap between the order date and the delivery date is too big, that could be accounted for a return behavior. So, because of this reason,our model needs a delivery date value and not NAs, which there is no way of predicting 100% correctly. Thus, they are excluded. Also, the if we don't exclude those values the model may predict a 0 whenever there is no delivery date, which is obviously not ideal and biased.

Item size¶

A remark:

The online retailer is guessed to be mainly a clothing retail. The reason for that is that sizes as "s, m, l, xl" are clearly top sizes and they constitute more than half of the orders in total. Some other example evidences are the high likelihood of "3332, 3432, 3632, 3832, 4032" item sizes being pants sizes for adults. Another could be "104, 116, 128, 140, 152, 164, 176" item sizes likely being EU-converted pant sizes for children.

  • Below the categorical and numerical item sizes are being seperated as the categorical ones needs to be encoded either with dummy or Weight-of-evidence method.
  • Also, some of the reasons why item sizes are handled early in the notebook are to be able to analyze them in the data exploration section and the flexibility it provides for the next steps such as standardization, feature selection, encoding and the like.

Data Type Adjustment¶

memory usage: 12.4+ MB

Having data type as object is not advantegous if we know what the data type of the variable should be because some libraries and functions only work with certain data types and object data type might not be aligned with those always

We will convert the data types that are more efficient and feasible so that our model can run.

In [50]:
#The target variable has only two states where the product is either returned (1), or it is not returned (0) 
#so that we can store it as the following.
dfk['return'] = dfk['return'].astype(int)

dfu[num_vars4] = dfu[num_vars4].astype(np.int32)

Explanatory Analysis¶

Some controversial missings: Item color has values of "?" and user title "not reported". These are essentially missing values but since there is a chance of these variables turning out to be not predictive for the model, the rows who include these values won't be excluded for now.

With the table above, we can see some general information about the variables, Some of which will also be further elaborated on below.

In [57]:
sns.distplot(dfk['item_price']);

In this density plot of item prices, one can observe how the distribution of the item prices are. There might be evidence for some outliers. Also, since the distribution of low and mediocre priced items is higher than the more expensive items, this might indicate, the online retail positioning itself as low to middle segment. If the shape of this graph was inverted (symettrical to 100 ), meaning that there are less products that are cheap and more that are more expensive, we would have an evidence of the possible positioning and the strategy of the retail store.

Data Partioning¶

In order to be able to assess our prediction model with a data set it has not seen before, replicating how our model would perform with the real unknown data, we split the data into two sets; namely, training and test data. For building the model training data will be used and for testing its performance the test data will be used and this will give more reliable and realistic results as the possibility of overfitting will be decreased.

In [75]:
np.random.seed(888)
split_sample = np.random.rand(len(dfk)) < 0.7 

dfk_train = dfk[split_sample]
dfk_test =  dfk[~split_sample]

Note: The return column is not splitted at the moment so that if any row has to be excluded it doesn't need to be excluded seperately. Also, data is partioned even before outlier and missing values handling because Interquantile range calculation (for truncation) and mean calculations (for imputation) will differ in the test and training set.

Outlier Handling¶

There are some reasons why outliers are not desirable. Some of these can be listed as: Outliers in supervised learning algorithms can result in poorer outcomes, they are not representative of the data so they create bias and lastly, they manipulate statistical calculations in a negative way, which may affect some of the important decisions that will depend on those calculations.

The boxplots below show whether there are some outliers in the numeric values, to which extent they are far from other observations etc.

In [78]:
dfk_train.item_price[:,].plot(kind = 'box', subplots=True);  #some outliers
In [79]:
dfk_train.user_age[:,].plot(kind = 'box', subplots=True);  #some outliers
In [80]:
dfk_train.user_reg_time[:,].plot(kind = 'box', subplots=True); #no outlier
In [81]:
dfk_train.order_day[:,].plot(kind = 'box', subplots=True);  #no outlier
In [82]:
dfk_train.delivery_day[:,].plot(kind = 'box', subplots=True);  #some outliers
In [83]:
dfk_train.delivery_dur[:,].plot(kind = 'box', subplots=True); #some outliers

There are many items that took quite some time to be delivered. These are outliers but since they are large in numbers and not some small number of exceptions they won't be truncated. The same way of thinking applies to the variable "delivery_day" too, which has a low chance to be predictive by only itself anyways.

In [84]:
# Truncation function 
def outlier_truncation(x, factor=1.5):
        
    # Calculate IQR
    IQR = x.quantile(0.75) - x.quantile(0.25) 
    
    # Define upper/lower bound
    upper = x.quantile(0.75) + factor*IQR
    lower = x.quantile(0.25) - factor*IQR
    
    # Truncation
    x[x < lower] = lower
    x[x > upper] = upper

    
    return x

dfk_train.item_price=outlier_truncation(dfk_train.item_price, factor=1.5)

Missing Values Mean Imputation¶

There are no missing values in the item price variable but there are some in the user age. The missing values in this variable will be replaced by the population mean and for the mean not to be affected by the outliers in the variable, this process is done after taking care of the outliers in the variable.

Scalization & Normalization¶

Normalization¶

Assumption of normality is an aspect that plays an important role while crucial decisions are being made for the model. In some cases, it can also be of importance when doing descriptive or predictive modelling. Because of these reasons, it is useful to normalize the variables, which we will do below.

Note: Also, since we might need to scale the data after the normalization once more, scalization is done after normalization.

In [107]:
dfk_train.select_dtypes(include='float32').hist(bins=30, figsize=(15, 10)); #Quick way to see which variables are likely to be normally distributed

Only user age is close to having a normal distribution.

Now we start normalization according to the order of histograms above.

Note: The normalization doesn't normalize the variables 100% percent but it normalizes them to some extent. Normalization of item price was quite distinct so it is normalized. In the preparation of this Notebook other variables were normalized too so that all of the variables are normalized a bit more and they are exposed to the same procedures (this is what I would do); however this lowered the AUC of the models. Also, the filter method table, which includes statistical calculations, was run when all of the variables were normalized and it gives the same results when they are not.

In [108]:
dfk_train_copy = dfk_train.copy() #as a backup in case of errors below
dfk_test_copy = dfk_train.copy()
dfu_copy = dfu.copy()

dfk_train_copy2 = dfk_train.copy() #as a backup in case of errors below
dfk_test_copy2 = dfk_train.copy()
dfu_copy2 = dfu.copy()

Delivery day¶

In [109]:
from scipy import stats 
from statsmodels.graphics.gofplots import qqplot #quantile-quantile plot
                                                 #the more the blue line matches with the red one, the likelier it becomes

Scalization¶

Scalization is an important step of the data preparation. Some distance based algorithms such as K-means or K-nearest neighbors perform better and more reliably with it. Also, some supervised learning algorithms, for example the ones that use gradient descent to optimize the equation such as logistic regression, perform better with scaled features. Because of that reason, below features are scaled within seperate data sets.

In [157]:

Feature Selection Methods¶

Filter methods are one way to effectively decide on which variables are worth keeping for the model and which are not. Since we have a discrete target variable (either return or keep the product), for the continuous variables we will be basing our decisions on the Fisher score and for the categorical variables on Information Value. Below is the implementation of the Filter methods table.

In [163]:
class filter_binary_target:                    #Implementation of the filter methods table
    def __init__(self, df, target):
        self.target = target
        self.data_head = dfk_train.head()

    def auto_filter_binary_target(self):
        print('Data must be in a clean pandas DataFrame. Categorical variables must be of data type bool or category. Continuous variables must be int64 or float64.')
        data_no_target = dfk_train.drop(columns=self.target)
        columns = ['Data Type', 'Metric', 'Score']
        index = data_no_target.columns
        result = pd.DataFrame(index=index, columns=columns)

        for col in data_no_target:
            if data_no_target.dtypes[col] == 'bool' or data_no_target.dtypes[col].name == 'category':
                result.loc[col, 'Data Type'] = "discrete"
                result.loc[col, 'Metric'] = "IV"
                result.loc[col, 'Score'] = self.IV_binary_target(feature=col)

            if data_no_target.dtypes[col] == 'int32' or data_no_target.dtypes[col] == 'float32':
                result.loc[col, 'Data Type'] = "continuous"
                result.loc[col, 'Metric'] = "Fisher"
                result.loc[col, 'Score'] = self.fisher_binary_target(feature=col)

        return result

    def IV_binary_target(self, feature):  
        data = pd.DataFrame()
    
        data['Count'] = dfk_train[feature].value_counts()
        data['Bad'] = dfk_train.groupby([feature])[self.target].sum()
        data['Good'] = data['Count'] - data['Bad']
    
        data["Distribution Bad"] = data["Bad"] / data["Bad"].sum()
        data["Distribution Good"] = data["Good"] / data["Good"].sum()
    
        data['WOE'] = np.log(data["Distribution Good"] / data["Distribution Bad"])
        data.replace({"WOE": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})

        data["IV"] = data["WOE"] * (data["Distribution Good"] - data["Distribution Bad"])

        iv = data["IV"].sum()

        return iv

    def fisher_binary_target(self, feature):
        mu_0 = dfk_train.groupby(dfk_train[self.target])[feature].mean()[0]
        mu_1 = dfk_train.groupby(dfk_train[self.target])[feature].mean()[1]
        var_0 = dfk_train.groupby(dfk_train[self.target])[feature].var()[0]
        var_1 = dfk_train.groupby(dfk_train[self.target])[feature].var()[1]

        num = abs(mu_0 - mu_1)
        den = (var_0 + var_1) ** 0.5
        score = num/den
    
        return score

Below, inf values will be fixed so that we can learn about how predictive the respective variable is. Also, Weight of Evidence coding will be done, which will be used for categorical variables in all three data sets. Since the calculation of WoE depends on the data set, for all three, it will be calculated seperately.

In [168]:
class IV_Calc_all:   #this code's aim is to fix the inf values and WoE encode the unknown data
    def __init__(self, dfk_all_copy, feature, target):
        self.feature = feature
        self.target = target
        self.data_head = dfk_all_copy.head()

    def count_values(self):
        data = pd.DataFrame()
        data['Count'] = dfk_all_copy[self.feature].value_counts()               # Count instances of each category, create row for each
        data['Bad'] = dfk_all_copy.groupby([self.feature])[self.target].sum()   # Count y=1 instances of that category
        data['Good'] = data['Count'] - data['Bad']                    # Count y=0 instances of that category
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
    
        try:
            assert data["Bad"].sum() != 0                               # Check that there are y=1 instances in sample
            assert data["Good"].sum() != 0                              # Check that there are y=0 instances in sample
            assert np.isin(dfk_all_copy[self.target].unique(), [0, 1]).all()      # Check that target includes only 0,1 or True,False
        except:
          print("Error: Target must include 2 binary classes.")
          raise                                                       # Stop running if one of the above conditions is not satisfied
    
        return data

    def distribution(self):
        data = self.count_values()
        data['Ratio Bad'] = data['Bad'] / data['Count']
        data['Ratio Good'] = data['Good'] / data['Count']
        data["Distribution Bad"] = data["Bad"] / data["Bad"].sum()    # Of all y=0 instances, what percentage are from each category?
        data["Distribution Good"] = data["Good"] / data["Good"].sum() # Of all y=1 instances, what percentage are from each category?
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-2:]
  
    def woe(self):
        data = self.distribution()
        data['WOE'] = np.log(data["Distribution Good"] / data["Distribution Bad"])
        data.replace({"WOE": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})  # If no instances are bad, this will replace values of infinity with 0
        data = data.sort_values(by=["WOE"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-1]
  
    def woe_adj(self):
        data = self.count_values()
        data["WOE_adj"] = np.log( 
            ((data["Count"] - data["Bad"] + 0.5) / (data["Count"].sum() - data["Bad"].sum())) / 
            ((data["Bad"] + 0.5) / data["Bad"].sum())
            )
        data.replace({"WOE_adj": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-1]
  
    def IV_per_cat(self):
        data = self.distribution()
        data['WOE'] = self.woe()
        data["IV"] = data["WOE"]*(data["Distribution Good"] - data["Distribution Bad"])
        data = data.sort_values(by=["IV"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-1]
  
    def full_summary(self):
        data = self.count_values()
        data['Ratio Bad'] = data['Bad'] / data['Count']
        data['Ratio Good'] = data['Good'] / data['Count']
        data["Distribution Bad"] = data["Bad"] / data["Bad"].sum()
        data["Distribution Good"] = data["Good"] / data["Good"].sum()
        data['WOE'] = self.woe()
        data["WOE_adj"] = self.woe_adj()
        data["IV"] = self.IV_per_cat()
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
        return data

    def final_assessment(self):
        data = self.full_summary()
        iv = data["IV"].sum() # final IV value
        if iv < .02:
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is not predictive with an IV of: {}".format(iv))
        elif iv < .1:
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is weakly predictive with an IV of:{}".format(iv))
        elif iv < .3:
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is moderately predictive with an IV of:{}".format(iv))
        else :
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is highly predictive with an IV of: {}".format(iv))
        return iv

The last two categorical item sizes' IV value is found to be infite. The reason for that is because there is only one case of each, which gives us an IV value of infinity as in "all" of the cases there has been either only a return or a keep. To receive an actual number for the IV value, we exclude them from the calculation temporarily.

In [188]:
class IV_Calc_train:   #the same code but only to get WoE values for the training set
    def __init__(self, dfk_train_copy, feature, target):
        self.feature = feature
        self.target = target
        self.data_head = dfk_train_copy.head()

    def count_values(self):
        data = pd.DataFrame()
        data['Count'] = dfk_train_copy[self.feature].value_counts()               # Count instances of each category, create row for each
        data['Bad'] = dfk_train_copy.groupby([self.feature])[self.target].sum()   # Count y=1 instances of that category
        data['Good'] = data['Count'] - data['Bad']                    # Count y=0 instances of that category
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
    
        try:
            assert data["Bad"].sum() != 0                               # Check that there are y=1 instances in sample
            assert data["Good"].sum() != 0                              # Check that there are y=0 instances in sample
            assert np.isin(dfk_train_copy[self.target].unique(), [0, 1]).all()      # Check that target includes only 0,1 or True,False
        except:
          print("Error: Target must include 2 binary classes.")
          raise                                                       # Stop running if one of the above conditions is not satisfied
    
        return data

    def distribution(self):
        data = self.count_values()
        data['Ratio Bad'] = data['Bad'] / data['Count']
        data['Ratio Good'] = data['Good'] / data['Count']
        data["Distribution Bad"] = data["Bad"] / data["Bad"].sum()    # Of all y=0 instances, what percentage are from each category?
        data["Distribution Good"] = data["Good"] / data["Good"].sum() # Of all y=1 instances, what percentage are from each category?
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-2:]
  
    def woe(self):
        data = self.distribution()
        data['WOE'] = np.log(data["Distribution Good"] / data["Distribution Bad"])
        data.replace({"WOE": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})  # If no instances are bad, this will replace values of infinity with 0
        data = data.sort_values(by=["WOE"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-1]
  
    def woe_adj(self):
        data = self.count_values()
        data["WOE_adj"] = np.log( 
            ((data["Count"] - data["Bad"] + 0.5) / (data["Count"].sum() - data["Bad"].sum())) / 
            ((data["Bad"] + 0.5) / data["Bad"].sum())
            )
        data.replace({"WOE_adj": {np.inf: 0, -np.inf: 0}})
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-1]
  
    def IV_per_cat(self):
        data = self.distribution()
        data['WOE'] = self.woe()
        data["IV"] = data["WOE"]*(data["Distribution Good"] - data["Distribution Bad"])
        data = data.sort_values(by=["IV"], ascending=False)
        return data.iloc[:,-1]
  
    def full_summary(self):
        data = self.count_values()
        data['Ratio Bad'] = data['Bad'] / data['Count']
        data['Ratio Good'] = data['Good'] / data['Count']
        data["Distribution Bad"] = data["Bad"] / data["Bad"].sum()
        data["Distribution Good"] = data["Good"] / data["Good"].sum()
        data['WOE'] = self.woe()
        data["WOE_adj"] = self.woe_adj()
        data["IV"] = self.IV_per_cat()
        data = data.sort_values(by=["Count"], ascending=False)
        return data

    def final_assessment(self):
        data = self.full_summary()
        iv = data["IV"].sum() # final IV value
        if iv < .02:
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is not predictive with an IV of: {}".format(iv))
        elif iv < .1:
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is weakly predictive with an IV of:{}".format(iv))
        elif iv < .3:
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is moderately predictive with an IV of:{}".format(iv))
        else :
            print("The variable " + self.feature + " is highly predictive with an IV of: {}".format(iv))
        return iv

                       #the same format with the other data sets

So, according to the filter methods table, now that we have also learned whether the variables which had a "inf" value for their IV score are actually predictive or not, we are ready to compare the performance of combination of the variables that were chosen by the help of statistical test with some other combinations, which is what is done in the next parts.

In the next section, we will try forward regression and backward selection feature selection methods and after those we will proceed with the model building. Since all of these require us to train models and test them, now is a good place to transfer the WoE encodes we have for train, test and the unknown data sets.

Brief Explanation: Both brand id and item id has turned out to be predictive of the return behavior, which has over 90 and 1915 values respectively. Since these are essentially categorical values, using the OneHotEncoder() function don't make sense because if it was used the model would suffer from the curse of dimensionality extensively. And it is not used for the other categorical variables such as user_title, which has fairly small number of categories, in order not to create inconsistency in the model when some variables use WoE encoding and the others OneHotEncoder().

Note: In an iteration before, all variables in all 3 data sets were encoded with adjusted WoE within the data sets however this decreased the AUC score the models give than the case where dfu variables, item id and brand id are replaced with adj_WOE and the rest normal WOE, which is done by the "scorecardpy".

Now, we need to apply the same process to the training and test sets as we need a model for the forward regression and backward selection feature selection techniques and to run a model we need to convert the categorical variables too, as we did with the unknown data.

Unlike above, now that we have the return column this time in the known data, we could WoE encode using the package scorecardpy to save from the time; however, because it is problematic with the id columns, the prior method is sticked to.

Note: Some of the categorical variables are replaced with the adjusted WoE's and not the plain WoE's because adjusted WoE is robust to missing values. Even though with some other variables we used adjusted WoE as well not to create inconsistencies between how the variables are treated within each seperate data set.

Forward Regression & Backward Selection¶

Forward Regression¶

Forward regression is a feature selection method where a variable is added in each iteration and the combination which gives the highest performance metric is displayed.

import statsmodels.api as sm

clf.fit(X_train,  np.ravel(y_train.values))

y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)

In [264]:
from mlxtend.feature_selection import SequentialFeatureSelector as SFS #on full data

clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=888, max_iter=1000, tol=0.01)
sfs = SFS(clf, 
           k_features=(3,12), 
           forward=True, 
           floating=False, 
           scoring='accuracy',
           cv=3)

sfs = sfs.fit(X, np.ravel(y.values))
print('best combination (AUC: %.3f): %s\n' % (sfs.k_score_, sfs.k_feature_names_))

best combination (AUC: 0.577): ('delivery_dur', 'item_size_num', 'order_day', 'user_reg_time', 'item_price', 'delivery_day', 'user_age', 'brand_id', 'item_color_woe', 'user_state_woe', 'user_title_woe', 'item_size_cat_woe')
In [265]:
clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=888, max_iter=1000, tol=0.01) #on training data
sfs = SFS(clf, 
           k_features=(3,13), 
           forward=True, 
           floating=False, 
           scoring='accuracy',
           cv=3)

sfs = sfs.fit(X_train, np.ravel(y_train.values))
print('best combination (AUC: %.3f): %s\n' % (sfs.k_score_, sfs.k_feature_names_))

best combination (AUC: 0.576): ('delivery_dur', 'item_size_num', 'user_reg_time', 'item_id', 'item_price', 'user_age', 'brand_id', 'item_color_woe', 'user_title_woe', 'item_size_cat_woe')

According to the filtering methods table user reg time, delivery duration, user age and user title were found to be not predictive of the returning behavior; however, here they are (likely because of some unobserved interactions between them or they might be increasing the AUC but very little). But it is important to keep in mind that these values maximize the AUC of the Logistic Regression model while our aim is to minimize the costs.

Backward Selection¶

In [269]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFECV
clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=888, max_iter=10000, tol=0.001)

rfecv = RFECV(estimator=clf, step=1, cv=2, scoring='accuracy')
X_train_new = rfecv.fit(X_train,  np.ravel(y_train.values))

print('Optimal number of features: {}'.format(rfecv.n_features_))

Optimal number of features: 4

Building the Models¶

Outline:

  • Logit
  • Decision Trees
  • Cross Validation
  • Hyperparameter tuning
  • Bias-Variance Trade-off
  • Random Forests
  • Extreme Boosting
  • Cost-sensitive Analysis

Logistic Regression¶

Logistic regression is a good candidate for classification problems, where it calculates probabilities by minimizing the negative log-likelihood function using gradient descent.

Sm_logit Model¶

In [273]:

Logit model scores 0.5704

Normally, sklearn is more suitable for predictive purposes and statsmodels for explanatory; however, here statsmodels performed slightly better unexpectedly. The reason could be that we didn't use any of the features of the logisticregression() function and also didn't hypertune it.

Above we have tried different combinations of variables and logit functions to see how they perform. Next we will check decision trees and after that random forest and boosting algorithms, which usually give better results.

Regularized Logistic Regression¶

Here we will try to reduce the error of the prior models by introducing some bias to the equation and increasing the variance so that the results are somewhat more balanced, a phenomenon known as bias-variance tradeoff.

In [314]:

Lasso Regularization¶

The aim of regularization is to introduce some bias to the model so that variance decreases (Bias-Variance trade-off). The optimization of this trade-off provides the minimum error that the model produces. Thus, it results in both better performance and more trust in the model as it also decreases the variance.

In [321]:
lasso_all = sm_logit_all.fit_regularized(alpha=7)  # the argument alpha controls the degree of regularization. 

print(lasso_all.summary())

Greedy Search Method¶

Greedy search method is an important method where we hypertune the parameters of an algorithm of some kind of based on the improvements in a metric of interest through out the iterations, which we will apply below.

We don't apply grid search method to a decision tree but rather to a random forest model as it has more potential to give higher results because it uses bagging (sampling with replacement) and random subspacing in creating predictions.

In [344]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedStratifiedKFold  #Regularization hypertuning
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
# define models and parameters
model = LogisticRegression()
solvers = ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear', 'saga']
penalty = ['l1','l2', 'elasticnet']
c_values = [100, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01]
# define grid search
grid = dict(solver=solvers,penalty=penalty,C=c_values)
cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=1)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=grid, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy',error_score=0)
grid_result = grid_search.fit(X, y)
# summarize results
print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV #Using grid search method combined with cross validation
print('Tuning random forest classifier')
rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=888, max_samples = 0.5)  # This way, bootstrap sample size will be 50% of the training set

# Define meta-parameter grid of candidate settings
# The following settings are just for illustration
param_grid = {'n_estimators': [100, 200, 500, 1000],
              'max_features': [1, 2, 4, 7, 10, 13]
              }

# Set up the grid object specifying the tuning options
gs_rf = GridSearchCV(rf, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='roc_auc', verbose=1)
fit=gs_rf.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel()) 
gs_rf.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())

import xgboost as xgb 
    # Setting up the grid of meta-parameters
xgb_param_grid = {
    'colsample_bytree': np.linspace(0.5, 0.9, 5),  # random subspace
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],  # ensemble size or number of gradient steps
    'max_depth': [5, 10],   # max depth of decision trees
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.01],  # learning rate
    'early_stopping_rounds': [10]}  # early stopping if no improvement after that many iterations

gs_xgb = GridSearchCV(estimator=xgb.XGBClassifier(), param_grid=xgb_param_grid, scoring='roc_auc', cv=5, verbose=0)
gs_xgb.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())

    'colsample_bytree': np.linspace(0.5, 0.9, 5),  # random subspace
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],  # ensemble size or number of gradient steps
    'max_depth': [5, 10],   # max depth of decision trees
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.01],  # learning rate
    'early_stopping_rounds': [10]}  # early stopping if no improvement after that many iterations

Cost matrix formulas are dependent on the item price, which means that for each item price there is a different cost. We calculate the mean of the item prices in the known and unknown data and use that for the calculation of the cost matrix. Although this may not minimize the costs fully it should decrease them to some extent.

In [401]:
# Calculating fpr and tpr manually at a given cutoff
# We will use this function to plot markers at distinct point across our line graph to see where the different cutoffs are along the graph
def tpr_fpr_calc(cutoff, yhat_prob, y_true):

    # temp variable giving distinct predictions based on the cutoff given as an input
    temp = (yhat_prob >= cutoff).astype(bool)

    # Create confusion matrix for this prediction
    cmat = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_true, temp)
    
    # Calculate FPR
    fpr = cmat[0,1] / (cmat[0,1] + cmat[0,0])

    # Calculate TPR
    tpr = cmat[1,1] / (cmat[1,1] + cmat[1,0])

    return tpr, fpr

In [420]:
# To calculate the error cost, we need to convert our predictions into the same format as the cost-matrix
cmat_default = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, pred_default)
cmat_bayes = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, pred_bayes)

# Calculate confusion matrix probabilities for each cell and multiply with cost-matrix to calculate the cost
print("The error cost for the default cutoff is: {}".format(np.sum(np.sum((cmat_default/len(y_test))*cost_matrix.T)))) # summarize to get total cost
print("The error cost for the cost-minimal cutoff is: {}".format(np.sum(np.sum((cmat_bayes/len(y_test))*cost_matrix.T))))

The error cost for the default cutoff is: 13.0500858993923
The error cost for the cost-minimal cutoff is: 12.517481710282729
In [421]:
# Save function to calculate error-cost including option to adjust cutoff
def calc_error_cost(y_probabilities, y_test, cutoff, cost_matrix_df):
    pred = np.where(y_probabilities >= cutoff, 1, 0)                    # convert class probabilities into class predictions
    cmat = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)                       # compute corresponding confusion matrix
    cost = (np.sum(np.sum((cmat/len(y_test))*cost_matrix.T))).round(5)  # calculate the corresponding cost
    return [cutoff, cost]

CV-method¶

In [426]:
# To use cross-validation we refer back to this function we defined in the model assessment tutorial
from sklearn.utils import shuffle
def cv_split(seq, splits):
  return (seq[i::splits] for i in range(splits))

# Define function for threshold tuning
def lowest_error_cutoff(k, X_train_df, X_test_df, y_train_true, y_test_true, bayes_cost_matrix, y_test_probabilities):
  cutoffs_total = [] # save best cutoff from each split here, so we can average this cutoff later

  # Create a list of the index of our full data set as input, and k for the amount of splits
  cv_split_list = list(cv_split(shuffle(X_train_df.index.values.tolist(), random_state=888), k)) 

  for fold, i in enumerate(cv_split_list): # for each split 

    temp = X_train_df.index.isin(i) # Create temp variable for data to exclude            
    X_train_cv, y_train_cv = X_train_df.iloc[~temp], y_train_true[~temp] # Build model on all but hold out data
    X_test_cv, y_test_cv =  X_train_df.iloc[temp], y_train_true[temp] # Test on hold out data later
    rf.fit(X_train_cv, y_train_cv) # Train model
    pred_temp_prob = rf.predict_proba(X_test_cv)[:, 1] # Calculate class probabilities for current split

    # Define empty variable to save all cutoffs and corresponding errors. This way we can extract the lowest one for this split later
    cutoffs_cv = []
    error_cost_cv = []

    for j in  np.arange(0, 1, 0.001): # np.arrange(from, to, step-size)
              pred_temp = (pred_temp_prob >= j).astype(bool) # convert probabilities to class predictions
              cutoffs_cv.append(j) # save corresponding cutoff
              temp_cutoff_cost = calc_error_cost(pred_temp, y_test_cv, j, bayes_cost_matrix) # calculate cost and cutoff using our previously function
              error_cost_cv.append(temp_cutoff_cost[1]) # save error for the given cutoff
      
    temp_df = pd.DataFrame({"cutoffs":cutoffs_cv, "error_cost": error_cost_cv}).sort_values("error_cost")  # merge cutoffs and error cost, sort from lowest to highest by error_cost
    print("This is the fold number {}".format(fold+1)," of the cross-validation")
    print("The lowest error on the holdout data was achieved with the following cut-off: {}".format(temp_df.iloc[0].values[0]))
    print("The corresponding error cost is: {}".format(temp_df.iloc[0].values[1]))
    print("")
    cutoffs_total.append(temp_df.iloc[0, 0]) # save the lowest cutoff of this split to the list so we can average it at the end
    plt.plot(temp_df.cutoffs, temp_df.error_cost) # plot cutoffs and corresponding errors
   
  temp_cutoff_cost= calc_error_cost(y_test_probabilities, y_test_true, np.mean(cutoffs_total).round(5), bayes_cost_matrix) # np.mean(cutoffs_total) is the resulting best cutoff from the cross validation. We calculate the corresponding error-cost on the test data set
  plt.plot(temp_cutoff_cost[0], temp_cutoff_cost[1], marker='x', markersize=20, alpha=1, color='black', label="Average cutoff performance on test data") # plot cutoff and corresponding error on test set
  plt.title("Error Cost on Holdout Data by Threshold")
  plt.ylabel("Error Cost")
  plt.xlabel("Threshold") 

  print("The best threshold according to cross-validated threshold tuning is: {}".format(temp_cutoff_cost[0])) 
  print("On the test set, it has the following error cost: {}".format(temp_cutoff_cost[1]))
  return temp_cutoff_cost

In [432]:
def MetaCost(X_train, X_test, y_train, relabel_model, final_model, optimal_cutoff):
  # Use model with good calibration to predict the new labels and create probability predictions
  temp_pred_proba_train = relabel_model.fit(X_train, y_train).predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]

  # Convert the probability predictions to class predictions using Bayes Decision Theory
  temp_pred_class_train = np.where(temp_pred_proba_train >= optimal_cutoff, 1, 0) # These are the new class labels

  # Fit a potent model to the test set, replacing our usual y_train with resulting class predictions from the last step
  final_model.fit(X_train, temp_pred_class_train)

  # Get predictions for the test set
  temp_pred_proba_test_cs = final_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

  return temp_pred_proba_test_cs

In [438]:
# Plot Confusion Matrix using Heatmap
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (24, 5)

import seaborn as sns
fig, ax_lst = plt.subplots(1, 4)
cmat_list = [cmat_default, cmat_bayes, cmat_CV, cmat_MC]
csm_types = ["Default", "Bayes", "Cross-Validation Threshold Tuning", "MetaCost"] # types of cost-sensitive methods

for i, j, ax in zip(cmat_list, csm_types, ax_lst.flat):

    # Plot heatmap
    ax.set_title(j)
    sns.heatmap(i, ax=ax, annot=True, fmt='g', cbar=False, xticklabels=['predicted 0', 'predicted 1'], yticklabels=['true 0', 'true 1'])
    
plt.show()

In order to minimize the total cost, (compared to the default cut-off) cost minimization algorithms chose to let the cases where we predict the item won't be returned but it is in reality returned increase so that the cases where we predict an item to be returned but it is kept are minimized.
